@knazeri,i have two questions.
Q1:You mentioned in the paper that your statistics in table 1 are calculated over 10,000 random images in the test set.How about celeba and PSV? What's the proportion of training set and validation set?
Q2:Have you tried only on HED?In my opinion,after performing element-wise multiplication on Canny and HED,you will lose the edge thickness of HED,which i think might be helpful.

@cmyyy 
Q1. For celeba dataset, we used 10,000 random images from the official test set. But for Paris StgreetView the test set is relatively small. What we did was to augment the test to 10,000 by using different mask shapes on the same test set!

Q2. We tried both. As we discussed in the paper, heuristically we found element-wise multiplication between the output of HED and Canny would result in very sketch looking edge-maps and the inpainting network (G2) can benefit a lot from those edge information (As you can see in table 5) but the problem is that our edge generator network (G1) fails to capture and reproduce the distribution and it remains an open question in our work.
